<font color="#FF0000">MEMORIAL</font><br>
<tt>Fri Dec 27  2:50:01 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
To Another Vietnam Vet:<br>
     Not intelligent?  What about the American Flag?  It is a widely known fact, that Maya Lin did oppose the flying of the American flag!  I remember this flag as being flown over my hootch in Vietnam.  It was a symbol of the country I fought for and was born in.  It doesn't seem wrong to you to have her be opposed to it flying there over the memorial to our brothers?  Does that memorial give a face to the friends we lost?  It just lists their names!  The faces and lives of our friends are only in our memories now.  Their voices are not heard by this memorial.  As for calling me stupid, it is your right as a citizen to call me that, we fought for that right.  I wouldn't call you stupid, obviously this strikes a cord with you also, for you to be writing here!  What I am saying is that there could have been a better way to remember our dead.  Yes, we need to remember who, but that list has no personal connection, no voice to someone who was not connected to this war by service and/or the loss of a loved one.  Why does it need to be below ground?  You tell me why it has to be imbedded in ground?  The flags on the coffins of our brothers were folded and never allowed to touch ground.  No memorial to our fallen should be like that, in the ground.  If you want to see a memorial with meaning visit the New York City memorial, it is on a rise, it is lit at night to stand out, as a constant light to the men still missing and to those we lost.  Written on it are the words that men wrote home.  These words give a voice to our comrades who died and to all of us that served.  I just don't like how the monument in Washington doesn't do this.  The statue of the nurse and soldiers are moving and help improve this memorial, but what right does Maya Lin have, to refuse their addition?
<p><code>--   (Nam Vet) </code><p>


